Classifications 

Logistic Regression
Predicting categorical values 
ie based on age, will be person perform an action(Yes/No), open an account (Yes/No) 
Model this. run a linear regression line through a dataset like this doesnt solve the problem. 

Instead of predicting, predict the likelihood or probability of that person 
taking that offer. 
so lets say there is an 80 percent chance that he will sign up. 
so thinking abt it that way, the linear regression line. 
basically saying, anybody between ages or where crossing the horizontal axis 
is 0(not sign up)(age 35) and 1(going to sign up)(age 55)
ages between that have probabilities of taking that offer and it increaes as we 
move to the right. 
so we have to adjust the linear regression line 
anyone one below ages 35 not going to sign up 
anyone above age 55 is going to sign up. 

Linear regression equation = y = bo + b1 * x 
sigmoid function, p = 1 / 1 + e pow -y 
apply sigmoid function to the logistic regression equation, and solve for y 
ln(p / 1 - p) = b0 + b1 * x, this is the formular of logistic regression. 
and this will convert the straight line in dataset to S-like line in the dataset. 
this is best fitting line, that can fit the dataset, 

Logistic regression graph 
X - axis(Probabilities) 
Y - axis (values) 
so lets say value is 20, phat is 0.7% meaning there is 0.7% chance a user who is 20 years will not sign up

inside logistic regression line, seperate it (0.5) 
anything below the line is projected downwards which is 0 
anything above the line is projected upwards which is 1  